XX. §46, 1. (a statement which their high character forbids us to doubt). Why should Cic. guard against such a doubt? The asser— tion is not one likely to be falsely made even by a man whose veracity is not unimpeachable. Gout could as a rule be proved without interrogating the sufferer. The expression banus uir is very osten ironical and it does not usually mean ‘a man of his word ' except in re- lation to commercial transactions.
